		\item 
			\begin{enumerate}
				\item
					To detect malicious errors, it is only necessary to add $\boxed{k}$ symbols.\\
					$k$ additional symbols are necessary to represent the polynomial.
					The $n$ symbols are represented as a polynomial of degree $d=n-1$.
					Suppose that $n+k$ symbols are sent through the channel.
					Any $n$ points uniquely determine a polynomial of degree $n-1$.
					Thus, if there are $n+k$ points, $k+1$ points must be maliciously corrupted to generate a valid polynomial.
					Hence, adding $k$ points will suffice to detect $k$ errors.
				\item
					To detect most nonmalicious errors, it is only necessary to add 1 point.
					Since the $k$ errors are not malicious, they are random changes to the data.
					Since the number of sets of $n+1$ points that align on a polynomial of degree 
					$n-1$ is vastly smaller than the set of $n+1$ points that don't, the probability 
					of a random change to the dataset to generate a set of $n+1$ points that do not generate an invalid polynomial is very low.
					Hence, $n+1$ points can detect most nonmalicious errors.
			\end{enumerate}
		\newpage
		\item
			The president should encode the launch code numerically, as a number $m$ create a polynomial $P(x)$ of degree $d=99$, $where P(0)=m$.
			He should then find 100 points on the polynomial, at values $x=1,2,3,\cdots,100$ to distribute among the 100 generals.
			Since there are at most 5 spies, $k=5$.
			9 or fewer generals cannot launch the missile, so $n=10$.
			As this situation will generate malicious errors, to ensure recovery, $N=n+2k=10+(2)(5)=20$ generals must be present.
			Thus, it takes a minimum of $N=20$ generals to guarantee the launch the missile.
