		\item
			\begin{enumerate}
				\item
					Suppose for contradiction that there is an odd cycle in some bipartite graph with sets A and B.
					Then, $\exists$ some point P, such that there is a path from P to P in an odd number of steps.
					Without loss of generality, assume that P is in A.
					By definition of bipartite graph, each each step of any path will go from A to B, or B to A; 
					there are no direct paths from A to A or B to B.
					Then, a step from P will be a path to a point in B.
					A step from B, in turn, goes back to A.
					Therefore, in every odd step, the path goes to a point in B.
					In every even step, the path goes to a point in A.
					So every odd step yields a point in B.
					But P is in A, and there exists an odd cycle in the graph.
					The graph must not be bipartite. Contradiction.
				\item
					By definition of bipartite graph with sets L and R, the only valid edges connect a point in L and a point in R.
					Therefore, each edge counts both for some point in L and some point in R.
					Suppose, now for contradiction, that $\sum_{v\in L} degree(v)\neq\sum_{v\in R} degree(v)$.
					For this to be true, there must be some edge that connects two points in R, or two points in L.
					By definition of bipartite graph, this cannot be the case. Contradiction.
			\end{enumerate}
